hetic_data['description'] = synthetic_data['description'].apply(synonym_replacement)\n\n# Sample 10,000 non-fraudulent entries from the synthetic data\nsynthetic_data_sampled = synthetic_data.sample(n=10000, random_state=42)\n\n# Combine with original dataset\ndf2 = pd.concat([df, synthetic_data_sampled])\n\n# Verify the balance\nprint(df2['fraudulent'].value_counts())\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-12-21T17:42:52.626681Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-12-21T17:42:52.627111Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-12-21T17:42:54.90008Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2024-12-21T17:42:52.627083Z","shell.execute_reply":"2024-12-21T17:42:54.898977Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"fraudulent\n1    10000\n0    10000\nName: count, dtype: int64\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":27},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### **Second Model: Using Synthetic Data by Synonym Replacement**\n\nIn this step, we will use the balanced dataset, which includes synthetic non-fraudulent data generated through synonym replacement, to train our model. We will split the dataset into training and testing sets to ensure that the model has distinct data for learning and evaluation. Following this, we will build a classification model using Logistic Regression and assess its performance on the test set.\n\nLet’s see if this approach improves our model’s ability to distinguish between fraudulent and non-fraudulent job postings.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Preprocess the text data in df2\ndf2['preprocessed_text'] = df2['text_column'].apply(preprocess_text)\n\n# Display the first few rows to verify the changes\ndf2[['text_column', 'preprocessed_text']].head()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-12-21T17:42:58.353658Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-12-21T17:42:58.35402Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-12-21T17:43:13.333053Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2024-12-21T17:42:58.353985Z","shell.execute_reply":"2024-12-